    # [Scene: Mangrove Patch / Abandoned Shipyard | Dusk]

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low cello with a hesitant piano — a melody that began hopeful and now trails off into a minor key]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant gulls, the soft suck of water against rusted hulls, a single footstep squelching in the mud]
    "You come back to this place because places keep the ledger better than people do. The mangrove remembers who planted the first frame and who left a kettle on the stove when the water climbed. It"
    "remembers the nights the town sang into the wind and the mornings it learned how to be quieter."
    "You can feel the pilot project's bones under your boots — engineered frames rooted where eelgrass once thinned, neat rows of seedlings knotted into the mud by apprentice hands. Up close, the cords and reclaimed beams"
    "look small against the horizon, human-scale stitches on a coastline that demands architecture of another order. They worked. For some things, they did what you promised you'd try to do: hold a line, buy a season,"
    "pull a fishery back from the edge."
    "Ilias Navarro kneels near a tray of newly sprouted blades, fingers gentle as a prayer. His breath fogs in front of him; the field tablet on his knee glows with tidal graphs. When he looks up,"
    "his ocean-blue eyes are wet with the kind of relief that has nothing to do with triumph and everything to do with breathing after fear."
    show ilias_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ilias_navarro "Look at this — look at how the shoot density jumped after the frames anchored. We bought growth time, Maya. We actually bought it."
    "His voice is small for the scale of what you're trying to hold together, but it reaches you like light on water. You want to tell him what his hope saves you from — nights you"
    "don't dare to name — and he gives you the thing you keep coveting: a quiet confidence that work can alter a map."
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "We bought it for now. Which is worth more than nothing."

    ilias_navarro "More than nothing is a direction. It's a proof."

    maya_kestrel "Proof doesn't pay for the buyouts that started this morning."
    hide ilias_navarro
    hide maya_kestrel

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A distant phone ping; someone laughs too loudly where no one should be laughing]
    "You tell yourselves, over and over, that pilots prove method. That data is armor against bulldozers and boardrooms. For a season, data was armor. Then the armor got weighed on scales that measure profit."
    "Rafi appears on the narrow path, camera hung from his neck, boots tracking the same mud. He stops before you, the expression on his face a hundred small shifts you have seen in his reporting: first"
    "excitement, then calculation, now something else you recognize too well — the pull toward elegy."
    show rafi_soto at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_soto "There's a piece on the feed. Headline's... it's honest. 'Patchwork Sanctuary Shows Promise — But Market Forces Redraw the Coast.'"
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "And the subhead?"

    rafi_soto "Sanctioned buyouts begin in three neighborhoods. Investors cite 'community realignment' and 'asset consolidation.' Mayor signed emergency clauses. Serenity Group — Seren's fund — will oversee compensated relocation."
    "The words compress in your chest. 'Compensated relocation' is a bureaucracy's lid over a crate of loss. You know the euphemisms; you cut your teeth on them. You also negotiated the governance clauses that kept a"
    "seat at the table. The clauses are there like stitches on a coat that is being pulled over an engine."
    show ilias_navarro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    ilias_navarro "We have the sanctuaries. We saved reef spawn routes. We saved Etta's lobster patch."

    maya_kestrel "We saved some places. Some people can start again here. But some will be told to start somewhere else — and they won't want to. They never ask to leave."

    menu:
        "Step closer to the seedlings, check the roots":
            "Your fingers find the cool, stubborn blades. Mud clings to your nails. For a moment you count roots like names you couldn't save and keep your hands busy."
        "Stand back on the plank and let Ilias examine them":
            "You fold your hands against your jacket and watch him work. It's less practical, but safer — less like tampering with things that might still break."

    # --- merge ---
    "You choose without choosing; hands that have mapped evacuation routes still remember how to soothe. The seedlings bite cold, living things that resist being turned into metaphors."
    hide rafi_soto
    hide maya_kestrel
    hide ilias_navarro

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Piano notes thin, then a low minor-key swell]
    "The headlines change the air. Investors speak in boardrooms you cannot enter; they speak about scaling the model you helped design until it is a product, until it fits other coasts and pays shareholders. Scalability and"
    "stewardship mean different things to different people. Yours is a map made of stitches and neighbors; theirs is a map that must be replicated by numbers."
    "Dr. Hana appears at the edge of the site, hands still damp from lab work, her coat flecked with kelp. She holds a tablet and a stack of grant sheets, the arc of her jaw weary and pragmatic."
    show dr_hana_sato at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_hana_sato "The tidal data supports your transplant method. But the clauses we negotiated are legal threads against heavy machinery with contracts. The fund's legal counsel left us room for consultation, not veto."
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "Consultation isn't veto."

    dr_hana_sato "No. Policy rarely is. But it's something. It kept sanctuaries off the demolition list this week."

    maya_kestrel "And next week?"

    dr_hana_sato "You're asking me to make guarantees I don't have the bandwidth to deliver."
    "Her candor is a lamp you don't want to look away from. She is not the kind of person to quiet the truth for your comfort. That steadiness is why she stood in the lab with you and why you trusted her numbers when people wanted miracles instead."
    # [Scene: Saltgarden Research Lab | Night]
    hide dr_hana_sato
    hide maya_kestrel

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Staccato strings underlaid with electronic hum; the room smells of sea salt and ethanol]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Soft typing, a kettle hissing in the distance]
    "You follow the arc of the day back to the lab because grief and work have the same shape for you: a list of things that must be done. Here, the math is cleaner: transplant survival"
    "rates, recruitment numbers, projected fish yields. But the lab is not immune to policy. There are memos and emails and a new dress code in city correspondence: 'relocation support operations' and 'orderly consolidation.'"
    "Ilias Navarro sits across the bench from you, tucking hair behind his ear. Sometimes you forget to be angry with him when he looks at you like the future is a hypothesis you can test together. Tonight he keeps glancing at the thread of a message he hasn't sent."
    show ilias_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ilias_navarro "They asked me to present at a consortium in two weeks. Funding for a regional roll-out. They want the method scaled. They... they also asked if the data could be used to recommend relocation zones where restoration 'isn't economically viable.'"
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "So your science will point to who stays and who goes."

    ilias_navarro "No. It will show where restoration works best according to the variables the fund cares about."

    maya_kestrel "Those variables are money."

    ilias_navarro "They're also survival metrics in some contexts. There's nuance. I know how this sounds —"

    "Maya Kestrel (interrupting)" "It sounds like you standing in the middle of a firing line because everyone thinks science looks good with a backdrop."

    ilias_navarro "I've always thought data could open options. Not close them."

    maya_kestrel "And what if the options are closed by a different ledger? What if your charts are used to sell permits for development where our sanctuaries should expand?"

    ilias_navarro "Then we'll fight it. Together."
    "He reaches for your hand across the bench; his fingers are warm and callused. For a while your shoulders loosen as if you can let something rest — but the relief is a taut thing, because rest here is a temporary harbor."

    menu:
        "Stay in the lab all night and run an extra simulation":
            "You mock up scenarios until numbers blur into the hum of the fluorescent lights. It's a refuge of form you can control."
        "Go with Ilias to the harborfront; see who else is packing boxes":
            "You pull on your coat and follow him outside. Seeing faces makes policy less abstract, even if it hurts more."

    # --- merge ---
    "You pick one. The lab hums as you leave, the night outside softer and salt-thick. Either way, the town keeps trimming itself along new fault lines."
    # [Scene: Hearthbend Harborfront | Late Night]
    hide ilias_navarro
    hide maya_kestrel

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse guitar plucking, like someone fooling a tune to stay awake]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmur of voices, a child's toy rolling in a box, a chair scraped once then left]
    "On the boardwalk, neighbors help one another load small treasures into crates. Some families leave with practiced patience, smiling as if to convince themselves. Others leave with the muttered curses of someone whose options were counted"
    "and found wanting. You recognize the faces who will be gone in a season: neighbors who rented the same room for thirty years; a boy who learned to tie nets under Etta's glove."
    "Etta sits in her dwindling shop, knitting the same pattern she has for half a lifetime. The lights inside make her a small island. When you step in, the smell of mended rope and fried fish wraps around you."

    "Etta (without looking up)" "You did what you could. Don't let numbers eat the rest."
    show maya_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "We kept the sanctuaries, Etta. We kept the eelgrass beds and the spawn routes. That matters."
    show etta_muir at right:
        zoom 0.7

    etta_muir "It matters to some. It doesn't matter to the ones already on the lists. You patched holes where they let the ship's hull go."

    maya_kestrel "We argued the clauses. We pushed the transparency. We —"

    etta_muir "— fought and wore everyone out. I remember when we had whole nets of cod that measured like summer. I remember when you were small and put a boat hook in your mouth thinking you were a gull."
    "She looks up then, and for a moment she is two things: the woman who taught your hands how to read tides and the moral compass the town returns to when it wants a true bearing. Her eyes are wet, but she knots the thread anyway."

    etta_muir "Keep knotting. Keep the recipes and the rights. Let the town remember how to reel in what it has left."
    "You nod. You cannot promise to stop the buyouts. You can only promise to keep knitting in the spaces they aren't paying for, to keep asking what it costs to save what you kept."
    hide maya_kestrel
    hide etta_muir

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The cello returns, each note a small, stinging recognition]
    "The cooperative you helped found has voice but not veto. Investors promised oversight with community input; the oversight has become a filter that sometimes leaves out the smallest names. Houses with certain property classifications are prioritized"
    "for compensation; others are offered loans and advice. It is not random — it is actuarial cruelty."
    "Rafi approaches, his camera down now. His piece that night is different: fewer exclamation points, longer pauses. He sits on the step where you once watched storms. There is a softness in his cadence that reads like a requiem."
    show rafi_soto at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_soto "People wanted a model. You made one that works for some. The headline will note that. It will also tell the story of the empty cul-de-sacs. That will get clicks too. But you should know — some of those families wrote to me after the buyout notices. They asked me to tell their names."
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "Tell them."

    rafi_soto "I will. They asked also to keep their dignity. They don't want pity; they want to be remembered as people who fished and mended and loved a place."
    "You think of the ledger again, and how ledger-keeping can be an erasure as much as an accounting. You are a planner who once believed the right map could save lives. Now you see how maps can also be used to redraw histories."
    # [Scene: Mangrove Patch | Dusk — Later]
    hide rafi_soto
    hide maya_kestrel

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single, sustained violin note that fades into the sound of water]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Two voices in low conversation, the soft slap of waves, crickets beginning their night chorus]
    "You return to the mangroves because you need to count the cost in a place that remembers roots. You stand at the waterline, the map of Hearthbend in your head split into areas where people will"
    "stay and areas that will empty. You trace the coastline with a thumb, watching neighborhoods vanish like a tide-line. The cooperative sits in the middle of the map now — a stitched square of sanctuaries and"
    "community gardens and terraced beds. It is a small miracle. It is also a scar."
    show ilias_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ilias_navarro "I keep thinking about the first time we planted seedlings. You pressed mud into my palm like a child trading a secret. We laughed when it rained on our faces."
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "I remember you singing under your breath when the water turned clear. I thought then that if the next storm tried to swallow us, we'd make a better face against it."

    ilias_navarro "We did make a better face."

    maya_kestrel "For some of us. For others, it wasn't enough."

    ilias_navarro "We knew it would never be perfect. But we also didn't expect the market to be the one to decide who remembers the coastline."

    "Maya Kestrel (bitter laugh)" "The market never asked the coastline what it wanted."

    "Ilias Navarro (searching)" "Do you regret we took the funding? That we signed the clauses?"
    "The question is a shard. You hold it, turning it with the same careful fingers you use on fragile seedlings. The cooperative's partial funding built the places people still fish from; without it, there may have"
    "been no sanctuaries at all. But without it, the pressure to scale and monetize might have not become the thing that hollowed whole streets."

    maya_kestrel "If we'd refused, the sanctuaries might have been crushed by faster, louder machines. If we'd accepted, we invited a logic that values scale over memory. I can see both ledgers now. Each has blood on it."

    ilias_navarro "Then how do we live with that?"

    maya_kestrel "We keep doing what we can for the people who stayed. We tell the stories of the people who left. We make room in the cooperative for names no one gave us permission to forget."

    ilias_navarro "And us?"
    "He reaches for you then, not with a plan but with presence. You rest your forehead against the flat of his palm. He smells of brine and the citrus of the lab wipes he uses to"
    "scrub instruments. For a while, all the maps and memos and obligations align around that small warmth."

    ilias_navarro "I don't have a plan that will fix everything. I only know I want to stay and keep trying. If you'll have me — in whatever patchwork we are left with."

    "Maya Kestrel (softly)" "I will try. But there will be nights when I wake thinking of the ones we couldn't save."

    ilias_navarro "I'll be awake with you."
    "Love is not a cure. It is not meant to be. It is a tether that keeps you from floating entirely free of the town you could not save. There is tenderness and also a terrible knowledge: this intimacy sits beside an irreversible re-mapping."
    hide ilias_navarro
    hide maya_kestrel

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Notes thin out; the violin ends on a dissonant but lingering chord]
    "You walk the edge of the mangroves and count. Some fisheries still hum. A few streets will ring with laughter again in a season. Etta's shop will shrink, but her hands will keep the nets mended"
    "as long as they allow it. Rafi will write elegies and triumphs in the same week. Dr. Hana will continue to prod at policy while knowing the limits of lab walls. Seren Blake — Seren will"
    "boast of 'regional stability' while sending letters of consolation to families she has made choices about."
    "You catalog what you saved: sanctuaries that rebounded; children who learned to plant eelgrass; a cooperative network now replicated in two other towns as a cautious example. You catalogue what you lost: a line of homes"
    "emptied under paper agreements, the shuttered bakery that taught everyone to fold dough at dawn, the old pier where your sibling once stood."
    "You touch the salt-stiff rope that anchors a frame and imagine a map with stitches so tight they leave white scars. You imagine the town as it will be: alive, reconfigured, bearing holes that will never"
    "be mended the way they once were. You think of the ledger — not as a single page to be closed but as an ongoing account you will keep."
    show ilias_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ilias_navarro "Do you ever think about leaving? For a place where maps are less... contested?"
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "Sometimes. But this is where the voices I love live. This is where people taught me how to calculate tides and how to say sorry and how to row a boat."

    ilias_navarro "Then we'll keep the stitches here. And when the market comes back with a sharper knife, we'll be ready to suture again."
    "He says it with the bravado of someone who believes hope is repeatable. You want to match his faith with your own. You don't quite manage it. Instead you fold your hands in your pockets and listen to the water."
    hide ilias_navarro
    hide maya_kestrel

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_9 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single slow chord, then silence except for the tide]
    "This rise was costly. The hybrid model opened doors and closed others. It saved hauls and heritage at the expense of neighborhoods that could not meet the new valuation of belonging. The town will heal around these losses like a body forming scar tissue — functional but forever marked."
    "You stand in the mangroves at dusk and name, in your head, the things kept and the things given up. Naming is its own kind of memorial: an act that refuses erasure. You whisper the names"
    "of empty streets, of people who left with their dignity intact, of those who stayed and will have to find new ways to be a town."
    "Ilias Navarro squeezes your shoulder. He does not pretend the wound isn't there. He does not promise it won't ache. He only says, plainly:"
    show ilias_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ilias_navarro "We'll tell the map as a story. Not as a solution. As a work in progress."
    "You let the map be a story for now. It's the best you can do. You also let the grief stay; it has earned the space in your chest to live. You will keep making plans,"
    "writing permits, arguing with counsel, mending nets, teaching apprentices. You will also learn how to accept compromise without letting it become erasure — a balancing act you will never perfect."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The faint sound of a distant siren, then the soft hush of the night]
    hide ilias_navarro

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_10 at full_bg
    "When you finally walk away from the water, you fold your notebook into your jacket and feel the familiar weight of maps and names. The town is alive but changed. Love remains, threaded through the work"
    "like kelp through pilings. The map is patched, yes, but patched with stitches you can see — and some of those stitches will fray."
    "You pause at the edge of the path and look back once. The sanctuary lights blink on like small beacons. The distant pier is a dark tooth. The town will keep remaking itself; you will keep"
    "remaking your work alongside it. The ledger is not closed. It is, you decide, a kind of promise to continue, even when the cost keeps mounting."

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_11 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade to quiet]

    scene bg ch13_f99e88_12 at full_bg
    "THE END"
